#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:127(title)
msgid "Index Support"
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:129(para)
msgid "The <filename>pg_trgm</filename> module provides GiST and GIN index operator classes that allow you to create an index over a text column for the purpose of very fast similarity searches. These index types support the <literal>%</literal> similarity operator (and no other operators, so you may want a regular B-tree index too)."
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:140(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nCREATE TABLE test_trgm (t text);\nCREATE INDEX trgm_idx ON test_trgm USING gist (t gist_trgm_ops);\n"
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:145(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nCREATE INDEX trgm_idx ON test_trgm USING gin (t gin_trgm_ops);\n"
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:137(para)
msgid "Example: <placeholder-1/> or <placeholder-2/>"
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:153(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nSELECT t, similarity(t, '<replaceable>word</replaceable>') AS sml\n  FROM test_trgm\n  WHERE t % '<replaceable>word</replaceable>'\n  ORDER BY sml DESC, t;\n"
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:150(para)
msgid "At this point, you will have an index on the <structfield>t</structfield> column that you can use for similarity searching. A typical query is <placeholder-1/> This will return all values in the text column that are sufficiently similar to <replaceable>word</replaceable>, sorted from best match to worst. The index will be used to make this a fast operation even over very large data sets."
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:165(para)
msgid "The choice between GiST and GIN indexing depends on the relative performance characteristics of GiST and GIN, which are discussed elsewhere. As a rule of thumb, a GIN index is faster to search than a GiST index, but slower to build or update; so GIN is better suited for static data and GiST for often-updated data."
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:175(title)
msgid "Text Search Integration"
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:177(para)
msgid "Trigram matching is a very useful tool when used in conjunction with a full text index. In particular it can help to recognize misspelled input words that will not be matched directly by the full text search mechanism."
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:188(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nCREATE TABLE words AS SELECT word FROM\n        ts_stat('SELECT to_tsvector(''simple'', bodytext) FROM documents');\n"
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:184(para)
msgid "The first step is to generate an auxiliary table containing all the unique words in the documents: <placeholder-1/> where <structname>documents</structname> is a table that has a text field <structfield>bodytext</structfield> that we wish to search. The reason for using the <literal>simple</literal> configuration with the <function>to_tsvector</function> function, instead of using a language-specific configuration, is that we want a list of the original (unstemmed) words."
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:203(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nCREATE INDEX words_idx ON words USING gin(word gin_trgm_ops);\n"
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:200(para)
msgid "Next, create a trigram index on the word column: <placeholder-1/> Now, a <command>SELECT</command> query similar to the previous example can be used to suggest spellings for misspelled words in user search terms. A useful extra test is to require that the selected words are also of similar length to the misspelled word."
msgstr ""

#: /home/carloratm/progetti/postgresql-source/doc-9.0.4/pgtrgm.xml:214(para)
msgid "Since the <structname>words</structname> table has been generated as a separate, static table, it will need to be periodically regenerated so that it remains reasonably up-to-date with the document collection. Keeping it exactly current is usually unnecessary."
msgstr ""

